The first known case of triplets from a giant panda was recorded in 1999, when a 15-year-old mother gave birth following artificial insemination in the southwestern Chinese city of Chengdu.

But the youngest of the trio died after living for just three days because of a bladder disorder.

The birth of rare panda triplets is a further success for China's artificial breeding program. 

